<paragraph id="8AE0B3F40DC4E497CA1AA1B14415341D" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="22D358510CCB603AC251B2364DFD9BAC" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Southern Spain (prov. Granada).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BC322FFDEB7B02E0121D95D3F37B8DA5" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="1CE85D580E7850F9E4B473B4E4D002DF" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="719F32052CF24C45E3147C4BDD30177C" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Host plant and early stages are unknown. The type series was collected at the end of April at unreported altitudes.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="27D479618C87B3C3853D64C365E758E4" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="B873912231E24FF7606AD107E2B7C8A6" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF42110BF262CA4BB539D75C0879535" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName id="60FA82F1F913E0D9F16E3938DF4BC997" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Megacraspedus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megacraspedus dejectella" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dejectella">Megacraspedus dejectella</taxonomicName>
was described from three specimens of both sexes collected in the surroundings of Granada, southern Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="1DEAF154D7AF7B9DCDBB38EE2E94FDEE" author="Staudinger, O" journalOrPublisher="Stettiner entomologische Zeitung" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" pagination="211 - 259" title="Diagnosen nebst kurzen Beschreibungen neuer andalusischer Lepidopteren." volume="20" year="1859">Staudinger 1859</bibRefCitation>
). We examined two males from the type-series, but were unable to trace the female. Staudinger did not state the female to be brachypterous, and one may wonder if he had a female - or if the unlabelled male in ZMHU represents the third type specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
